      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">🧠</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Beginner Intuition</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 01 — Simple Mental Model</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="note note-mental">
        <div class="note-label">🧠 Mental Model</div>
        <p>Think of the shell as a <strong>very obedient assistant</strong> who only speaks text. You type a sentence (command), it reads it, runs off, does the task, and reports back in text. The <strong>terminal</strong> is the window you open to talk to this assistant. The <strong>shell</strong> is the assistant itself — the program interpreting your words.</p>
      </div>

      <p>Imagine your computer is a city. The <strong>kernel</strong> is the city's infrastructure — roads, electricity, water. The <strong>shell</strong> is the city hall interface where citizens (you) make requests: "give me this file", "run this program", "tell me who's logged in". The city processes those requests and gives you back a report.</p>

      <p>When you open a terminal, the shell starts and immediately shows you a <strong>prompt</strong> — that blinking cursor waiting for your input. Everything you type after that prompt is a command.</p>

      <pre><code><span class="output">ubuntu@myserver:~$</span> <span class="cmd-name">ls</span>
<span class="output">Documents  Downloads  Music  Pictures</span>

<span class="comment"># Breakdown of the prompt:
# ubuntu     = your username
# myserver   = the machine's hostname
# ~          = your current directory (~ = home directory)
# $          = you are a regular user (# means root/superuser)</span></code></pre>

      <div class="note note-try">
        <div class="note-label">✅ Try It Now</div>
        <p>Open your terminal right now. Look at the prompt. Can you identify your username, hostname, and current directory? Type <code>whoami</code> and press Enter. What did it print?</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- S2: Core Fundamentals -->
    <div class="section" id="s2">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">📖</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Core Fundamentals</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 02 — The building blocks</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>What is a shell?</h3>
      <p>A shell is a <strong>command interpreter</strong> — a program that reads your text input, interprets it as commands, executes them by talking to the OS kernel, and returns results as text output. Every Linux system has at least one shell.</p>

      <table>
        <tr><th>Shell</th><th>Full Name</th><th>Default On</th><th>Key Feature</th></tr>
        <tr><td><code>bash</code></td><td>Bourne Again Shell</td><td>Ubuntu, Debian</td><td>Most common. Scripting standard.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>sh</code></td><td>POSIX Shell</td><td>All Unix</td><td>Minimal, portable scripts</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>zsh</code></td><td>Z Shell</td><td>macOS (default)</td><td>Better autocomplete, plugins</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>fish</code></td><td>Friendly Interactive Shell</td><td>Optional install</td><td>User-friendly, syntax highlighting</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>dash</code></td><td>Debian Almquist Shell</td><td>Ubuntu (as /bin/sh)</td><td>Tiny, fast — used for boot scripts</td></tr>
      </table>

      <div class="note note-mental">
        <div class="note-label">🧠 Mental Model — Shell vs Terminal</div>
        <p><strong>Terminal</strong> = the glass window/app (gnome-terminal, iTerm, xterm, PuTTY). <strong>Shell</strong> = the program running <em>inside</em> that window interpreting your commands. You can run a different shell inside any terminal.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Anatomy of a command</h3>
      <p>Every command follows this basic structure:</p>

      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">command</span> <span class="flag">-options</span> <span class="string">argument1 argument2</span>

<span class="comment"># Real example:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-la</span> <span class="string">/home/ubuntu</span>

<span class="comment"># ls     = the command (list files)
# -la    = options: -l (long format) + -a (show hidden files)
# /home/ubuntu = argument (which directory to list)</span></code></pre>

      <h3>How the shell finds commands</h3>
      <p>When you type <code>ls</code>, the shell doesn't magically know where <code>ls</code> lives. It searches through a list of directories called the <strong>PATH</strong>. First match wins.</p>

      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$PATH</span>
<span class="output">/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin</span>

<span class="comment"># The shell checks each directory left to right
# The first 'ls' it finds in those directories is what runs</span>

<span class="cmd-name">which</span> <span class="string">ls</span>
<span class="output">/usr/bin/ls</span>

<span class="comment"># which tells you exactly which file will run</span></code></pre>

      <h3>Types of commands</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type</th><th>What it is</th><th>Example</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Built-in</td><td>Part of the shell itself — no file needed</td><td><code>cd</code>, <code>echo</code>, <code>export</code>, <code>alias</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>External</td><td>A binary file on disk, found via PATH</td><td><code>ls</code>, <code>grep</code>, <code>curl</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Alias</td><td>A shortcut you define</td><td><code>alias ll='ls -la'</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td>Function</td><td>A named block of shell code</td><td>Defined in scripts or <code>.bashrc</code></td></tr>
      </table>

      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">type</span> <span class="string">cd</span>
<span class="output">cd is a shell builtin</span>

<span class="cmd-name">type</span> <span class="string">ls</span>
<span class="output">ls is /usr/bin/ls</span>

<span class="cmd-name">type</span> <span class="string">ll</span>
<span class="output">ll is aliased to 'ls -la'</span></code></pre>
    </div>

    <!-- S3: Commands -->
    <div class="section" id="s3">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">⚙️</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Commands & Syntax</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 03 — Essential shell commands and operators</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Navigation</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">pwd</span>                    <span class="comment"># print working directory — where am I?</span>
<span class="output">/home/ubuntu</span>

<span class="cmd-name">cd</span> <span class="string">/etc</span>               <span class="comment"># change to /etc directory (absolute path)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cd</span> <span class="string">Documents</span>          <span class="comment"># change to Documents (relative to current dir)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cd</span> <span class="string">..</span>                  <span class="comment"># go up one directory</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cd</span> <span class="string">../..</span>              <span class="comment"># go up two directories</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cd</span> <span class="string">~</span>                   <span class="comment"># go to your home directory</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cd</span> <span class="string">-</span>                   <span class="comment"># go back to previous directory (very useful!)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cd</span>                     <span class="comment"># cd with no argument = go home</span></code></pre>

      <h3>Listing files</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">ls</span>                     <span class="comment"># list files in current directory</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-l</span>                  <span class="comment"># long format: permissions, owner, size, date</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-a</span>                  <span class="comment"># show hidden files (starting with .)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-la</span>                 <span class="comment"># both: long format + hidden</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-lh</span>                 <span class="comment"># human-readable sizes (KB, MB, GB)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-lt</span>                 <span class="comment"># sort by modification time (newest first)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-ltr</span>                <span class="comment"># sort by time, reverse (oldest first)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-R</span>                  <span class="comment"># recursive — show all subdirectories too</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="string">/etc</span>               <span class="comment"># list files in /etc directory</span>

<span class="comment"># Reading ls -l output:</span>
<span class="output">drwxr-xr-x  2 ubuntu ubuntu 4096 Jan 15 10:30 Documents</span>
<span class="comment"># d         = type: d=directory, -=file, l=symlink
# rwxr-xr-x = permissions (owner/group/others)
# 2         = hard link count
# ubuntu    = owner username
# ubuntu    = group name
# 4096      = size in bytes
# Jan 15    = last modified date
# Documents = name</span></code></pre>

      <h3>I/O Redirection — The superpower of the shell</h3>
      <p>Commands read from <strong>stdin</strong> (keyboard by default) and write to <strong>stdout</strong> (screen by default). Redirection lets you change where they read/write.</p>

      <table>
        <tr><th>Operator</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&gt;</code></td><td>Redirect stdout to file (overwrites)</td><td><code>echo "hi" &gt; file.txt</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&gt;&gt;</code></td><td>Append stdout to file</td><td><code>echo "hi" &gt;&gt; file.txt</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&lt;</code></td><td>Read stdin from file</td><td><code>sort &lt; names.txt</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>2&gt;</code></td><td>Redirect stderr to file</td><td><code>cmd 2&gt; errors.log</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>2&gt;&amp;1</code></td><td>Redirect stderr to same place as stdout</td><td><code>cmd &gt; out.log 2&gt;&amp;1</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>&amp;&gt;</code></td><td>Redirect both stdout+stderr (bash only)</td><td><code>cmd &amp;&gt; all.log</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>/dev/null</code></td><td>Discard output (the black hole)</td><td><code>cmd &gt; /dev/null 2&gt;&amp;1</code></td></tr>
      </table>

      <pre><code><span class="comment"># Save command output to file:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-la</span> <span class="string">/etc</span> <span class="output">&gt;</span> <span class="string">etc_listing.txt</span>

<span class="comment"># Append to a log:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">date</span> <span class="output">&gt;&gt;</span> <span class="string">activity.log</span>

<span class="comment"># Silence all output (common in cron jobs):</span>
<span class="cmd-name">./backup.sh</span> <span class="output">&gt; /dev/null 2&gt;&amp;1</span>

<span class="comment"># Capture errors separately:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">./deploy.sh</span> <span class="output">&gt;</span> <span class="string">out.log</span> <span class="output">2&gt;</span> <span class="string">err.log</span></code></pre>

      <h3>Pipes — Chaining commands together</h3>
      <div class="note note-mental">
        <div class="note-label">🧠 Mental Model</div>
        <p>A pipe <code>|</code> connects the output of one command directly into the input of the next — like an assembly line. The first command finishes processing, hands results to the second, which hands to the third.</p>
      </div>

      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-la</span> | <span class="cmd-name">grep</span> <span class="string">"txt"</span>       <span class="comment"># list files, then filter for lines containing "txt"</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ps</span> <span class="flag">aux</span> | <span class="cmd-name">grep</span> <span class="string">"nginx"</span>    <span class="comment"># list all processes, filter for nginx</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cat</span> <span class="string">access.log</span> | <span class="cmd-name">sort</span> | <span class="cmd-name">uniq</span> <span class="flag">-c</span> | <span class="cmd-name">sort</span> <span class="flag">-rn</span> | <span class="cmd-name">head</span> <span class="flag">-20</span>
<span class="comment"># ^ read log → sort alphabetically → count unique lines
#   → sort by count (descending) → show top 20
# This pattern is used DAILY in real production work</span></code></pre>

      <h3>Command chaining operators</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">cmd1</span> ; <span class="cmd-name">cmd2</span>            <span class="comment"># run cmd2 after cmd1, regardless of success</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cmd1</span> && <span class="cmd-name">cmd2</span>           <span class="comment"># run cmd2 ONLY if cmd1 succeeded (exit code 0)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cmd1</span> || <span class="cmd-name">cmd2</span>           <span class="comment"># run cmd2 ONLY if cmd1 failed</span>

<span class="comment"># Real world — safe deployment pattern:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">git pull</span> && <span class="cmd-name">make build</span> && <span class="cmd-name">./deploy.sh</span>
<span class="comment"># Only deploy if pull succeeded AND build succeeded</span></code></pre>

      <h3>History and shortcuts</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">history</span>                <span class="comment"># show command history (last 500 by default)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">history</span> <span class="flag">20</span>             <span class="comment"># show last 20 commands</span>
!<span class="string">42</span>                    <span class="comment"># re-run command number 42 from history</span>
!!                     <span class="comment"># re-run the last command</span>
!<span class="string">ls</span>                    <span class="comment"># re-run the most recent command starting with 'ls'</span>
<span class="flag">Ctrl+R</span>                 <span class="comment"># reverse search through history (type to filter)</span>
<span class="flag">Ctrl+C</span>                 <span class="comment"># interrupt/kill current running command</span>
<span class="flag">Ctrl+D</span>                 <span class="comment"># send EOF (exit shell or end input)</span>
<span class="flag">Ctrl+L</span>                 <span class="comment"># clear screen (same as 'clear' command)</span>
<span class="flag">Ctrl+A</span>                 <span class="comment"># move cursor to beginning of line</span>
<span class="flag">Ctrl+E</span>                 <span class="comment"># move cursor to end of line</span>
<span class="flag">Ctrl+W</span>                 <span class="comment"># delete word before cursor</span>
<span class="flag">Alt+.</span>                  <span class="comment"># paste the last argument of the previous command</span>
<span class="flag">Tab</span>                    <span class="comment"># autocomplete commands, files, and paths</span>
<span class="flag">Tab Tab</span>                <span class="comment"># show all possible completions</span></code></pre>

      <h3>Useful day-to-day commands</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">"hello"</span>           <span class="comment"># print text to stdout</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cat</span> <span class="string">file.txt</span>           <span class="comment"># print entire file contents</span>
<span class="cmd-name">less</span> <span class="string">file.txt</span>          <span class="comment"># view file with pagination (q to quit)</span>
