      <div class="note note-files">
        <div class="note-label">📁 Key Files</div>
        <p>The shell reads several files at startup to configure your environment. Knowing which file to edit for what purpose is critical — editing the wrong file is a very common source of confusion.</p>
      </div>

      <table>
        <tr><th>File</th><th>When loaded</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
        <tr><td><code>~/.bashrc</code></td><td>Every new interactive non-login shell</td><td>Aliases, functions, PS1 prompt, interactive settings</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>~/.bash_profile</code></td><td>Login shells only (SSH, console login)</td><td>Sets PATH, env vars — usually sources .bashrc</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>~/.profile</code></td><td>Login shells (if .bash_profile absent)</td><td>POSIX-compatible env setup</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>~/.bash_logout</code></td><td>On logout</td><td>Cleanup tasks (clear screen, etc.)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>~/.bash_history</code></td><td>Read/written on exit</td><td>Stores your command history</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>/etc/bash.bashrc</code></td><td>System-wide</td><td>Shared interactive bash settings for all users</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>/etc/profile</code></td><td>System-wide login</td><td>Shared login shell settings for all users</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>/etc/environment</code></td><td>System-wide at login</td><td>Global environment variables (not shell-specific)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>/bin/bash</code></td><td>—</td><td>The bash binary itself</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>/etc/shells</code></td><td>—</td><td>List of valid login shells on the system</td></tr>
      </table>

      <h3>Shell startup order (login shell)</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="comment"># When you SSH into a server, this is the load order:</span>
<span class="output">/etc/profile</span>           <span class="comment"># 1st: system-wide profile (runs /etc/profile.d/*.sh)</span>
<span class="output">~/.bash_profile</span>        <span class="comment"># 2nd: user's login profile</span>
  <span class="output">→ sources ~/.bashrc</span>  <span class="comment"># .bash_profile should call: [ -f ~/.bashrc ] && . ~/.bashrc</span>
<span class="output">~/.bashrc</span>              <span class="comment"># 3rd: interactive settings loaded</span></code></pre>

      <h3>Environment variables</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="cmd-name">env</span>                    <span class="comment"># print all current environment variables</span>
<span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$HOME</span>             <span class="comment"># print your home directory</span>
<span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$USER</span>             <span class="comment"># print your username</span>
<span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$SHELL</span>            <span class="comment"># print path to your current shell</span>
<span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$PATH</span>             <span class="comment"># print your search path</span>
<span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$?</span>               <span class="comment"># print exit code of the last command (0=success)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$$</span>               <span class="comment"># print the PID of the current shell</span>

<span class="comment"># Setting variables:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">MY_VAR</span>=<span class="string">"hello"</span>         <span class="comment"># set local variable (only this shell session)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">export</span> <span class="string">MY_VAR="hello"</span>  <span class="comment"># set and EXPORT (child processes inherit it)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">unset</span> <span class="string">MY_VAR</span>           <span class="comment"># remove a variable</span>

<span class="comment"># Add a directory to PATH:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">export</span> <span class="string">PATH="$PATH:/home/ubuntu/scripts"</span></code></pre>

      <div class="note note-warn">
        <div class="note-label">⚠️ Common Mistake</div>
        <p>Spaces around <code>=</code> break variable assignment. <code>MY_VAR = "hello"</code> fails. It must be <code>MY_VAR="hello"</code> with no spaces. This trips up everyone at first.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- S5: Under the Hood -->
    <div class="section" id="s5">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">🔬</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Under the Hood</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 05 — How the shell actually works internally</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="note note-hood">
        <div class="note-label">🔬 Under the Hood</div>
        <p>When you press Enter, bash performs a precise sequence of steps — not just "run the command". Understanding this sequence explains many confusing behaviours.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Command execution pipeline</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="comment"># When you type: ls -la /home | grep ubuntu</span>
<span class="comment"># Bash does ALL of this:</span>

<span class="output">1. Tokenization</span>    <span class="comment"># Split into tokens: "ls", "-la", "/home", "|", "grep", "ubuntu"</span>
<span class="output">2. Parse</span>           <span class="comment"># Identify pipeline structure</span>
<span class="output">3. Expansions</span>      <span class="comment"># Process $VAR, ~, *, glob patterns, backticks</span>
<span class="output">4. Redirect setup</span>  <span class="comment"># Wire pipe between ls stdout and grep stdin</span>
<span class="output">5. fork()</span>          <span class="comment"># Kernel creates a copy of the bash process</span>
<span class="output">6. exec()</span>          <span class="comment"># Child process replaces itself with /usr/bin/ls</span>
<span class="output">7. wait()</span>          <span class="comment"># Bash waits for child to finish</span>
<span class="output">8. Exit code</span>       <span class="comment"># Bash stores result in $?</span></code></pre>

      <h3>File descriptors</h3>
      <p>Every running process has a table of <strong>file descriptors</strong> — numbered connections to I/O streams. This is why redirection works the way it does.</p>
      <table>
        <tr><th>FD Number</th><th>Name</th><th>Default connection</th></tr>
        <tr><td><code>0</code></td><td>stdin</td><td>Your keyboard</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>1</code></td><td>stdout</td><td>Your terminal screen</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>2</code></td><td>stderr</td><td>Your terminal screen (errors)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>3+</code></td><td>Other files</td><td>Files your program opens</td></tr>
      </table>

      <pre><code><span class="comment"># Why cmd > file.txt 2>&1 works:
# 1. ">" redirects FD1 (stdout) to file.txt
# 2. "2>&1" says: make FD2 (stderr) point to whatever FD1 points to
# 3. Both now write to file.txt
# ORDER MATTERS: 2>&1 > file.txt would NOT redirect stderr to file!</span></code></pre>

      <h3>Subshells and forking</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="comment"># Parentheses create a SUBSHELL — changes don't affect parent</span>
(cd /tmp && ls)        <span class="comment"># cd happens in subshell; you stay in your current dir</span>
<span class="cmd-name">pwd</span>                    <span class="comment"># still in original directory!</span>

<span class="comment"># vs. running commands directly — affects current shell:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cd</span> /tmp && <span class="cmd-name">ls</span>          <span class="comment"># you ARE now in /tmp</span></code></pre>

      <h3>Shell expansions (order matters)</h3>
      <pre><code><span class="comment"># Bash expands these IN ORDER before running the command:</span>

<span class="output">1. Brace expansion:     </span><span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">{a,b,c}</span>         → a b c
<span class="output">2. Tilde expansion:     </span><span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">~</span>              → /home/ubuntu
<span class="output">3. Variable expansion:  </span><span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$HOME</span>          → /home/ubuntu
<span class="output">4. Command substitution:</span><span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$(date)</span>       → Mon Jan 15 10:30:00
<span class="output">5. Arithmetic:          </span><span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$((2+2))</span>      → 4
<span class="output">6. Glob expansion:      </span><span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="string">*.txt</span>          → all .txt files</code></pre>
