    <!-- S8: Beginner Mistakes -->
    <div class="section" id="s8">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Common Beginner Mistakes</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 08 — What trips everyone up at first</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="note note-warn">
        <div class="note-label">⚠️ Common Mistakes</div>
        <p>Every Linux beginner makes these mistakes. Read them now so you can avoid them.</p>
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Using spaces in variable assignment:</strong> <code>MY_VAR = "value"</code> fails. Must be <code>MY_VAR="value"</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Confusing <code>></code> and <code>>></code>:</strong> <code>></code> destroys the existing file first. <code>>></code> appends. Many people accidentally overwrite important files.</li>
        <li><strong>Not quoting variables with spaces:</strong> <code>cp $FILE /dest</code> breaks if <code>$FILE</code> contains spaces. Always use <code>cp "$FILE" /dest</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Case sensitivity:</strong> <code>Documents</code> and <code>documents</code> are different directories on Linux. <code>ls Documents</code> ≠ <code>ls documents</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Confusing <code>.</code> (source) and executing a script:</strong> Running <code>./script.sh</code> uses a subshell. Running <code>. ./script.sh</code> or <code>source script.sh</code> runs it in the current shell (exports variables into your session).</li>
        <li><strong>Forgetting tab completion:</strong> Typing full paths manually is slow and error-prone. Tab is your best friend.</li>
        <li><strong>Not checking exit codes:</strong> Commands fail silently. Use <code>echo $?</code> after each command until it becomes second nature.</li>
        <li><strong>Panic at "permission denied":</strong> Not a disaster — just means you need to check ownership and use the right user.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- S9: Production Mistakes -->
    <div class="section" id="s9">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">🏗️</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Common Production Mistakes</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 09 — What causes real outages</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Running destructive commands as root without double-checking:</strong> <code>rm -rf /tmp /myapp</code> — notice the accidental space. This removes <code>/tmp</code> and <code>/myapp</code> separately. Always use <code>echo</code> to test first.</li>
        <li><strong>Modifying <code>.bashrc</code>/<code>.bash_profile</code> without testing:</strong> A syntax error will lock you out of your shell session in the future. Always test with <code>bash -n ~/.bashrc</code> before sourcing.</li>
        <li><strong>Setting <code>PATH=""</code> or removing directories from PATH:</strong> You lose access to all external commands. Type full paths like <code>/bin/ls</code> to recover.</li>
        <li><strong>Overwriting files with <code>></code> in critical directories:</strong> <code>echo "test" > /etc/hosts</code> destroys your DNS configuration instantly. No undo.</li>
        <li><strong>Piping live data into <code>rm</code>:</strong> Always dry-run with <code>echo</code> or <code>ls</code> before <code>xargs rm</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Leaving debug <code>set -x</code> in production scripts:</strong> Floods logs, exposes secrets in output.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="note note-sec">
        <div class="note-label">🔐 Security Note</div>
        <p>Never put secrets (passwords, API keys, tokens) in shell commands — they appear in <code>history</code> and in <code>/proc/&lt;pid&gt;/cmdline</code>. Use environment variables loaded from a secrets manager, or read from files with restricted permissions.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- S10: Debug Workflow -->
    <div class="section" id="s10">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">🛠</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Debugging Workflow</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 10 — Systematic approach to shell problems</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="note note-debug">
        <div class="note-label">🛠 Debugging Workflow</div>
        <p>When something doesn't work in the shell, follow this checklist systematically instead of guessing randomly.</p>
      </div>

      <pre><code><span class="comment"># Step 1: Check the exit code</span>
<span class="cmd-name">some_command</span>
<span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$?</span>           <span class="comment"># 0 = success, anything else = failure</span>

<span class="comment"># Step 2: Check if the command exists and where it is</span>
<span class="cmd-name">which</span> <span class="string">mycommand</span>
<span class="cmd-name">type</span> <span class="string">mycommand</span>

<span class="comment"># Step 3: Check PATH if command not found</span>
<span class="cmd-name">echo</span> <span class="string">$PATH</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="string">/usr/local/bin/mycommand</span>   <span class="comment"># does the file exist?</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-la</span> <span class="string">/usr/local/bin/mycommand</span> <span class="comment"># is it executable?</span>

<span class="comment"># Step 4: Run with verbose/debug flags</span>
<span class="cmd-name">bash</span> <span class="flag">-x</span> <span class="string">myscript.sh</span>   <span class="comment"># trace every command as it executes</span>
<span class="cmd-name">bash</span> <span class="flag">-n</span> <span class="string">myscript.sh</span>   <span class="comment"># check syntax only, don't run</span>

<span class="comment"># Step 5: Check environment variables</span>
<span class="cmd-name">env</span> | <span class="cmd-name">grep</span> <span class="string">MY_VAR</span>     <span class="comment"># is the variable actually set?</span>

<span class="comment"># Step 6: Check for permission issues</span>
<span class="cmd-name">ls</span> <span class="flag">-la</span> <span class="string">thefile</span>        <span class="comment"># who owns it? what permissions?</span>
<span class="cmd-name">id</span>                     <span class="comment"># what user and groups am I?</span>

<span class="comment"># Step 7: Capture and inspect stderr separately</span>
<span class="cmd-name">mycommand</span> <span class="output">2>&1</span> | <span class="cmd-name">tee</span> <span class="string">debug.log</span>   <span class="comment"># see AND save output</span></code></pre>
    </div>

    <!-- S11: Security -->
    <div class="section" id="s11">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">🔐</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Security Considerations</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 11 — Shell security from day one</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Never pipe curl to bash in production:</strong> <code>curl https://... | bash</code> executes untrusted code directly. Download, inspect, then run.</li>
        <li><strong>Shell history is a risk:</strong> Passwords typed in commands are stored in <code>~/.bash_history</code>. Set <code>HISTCONTROL=ignorespace</code> — commands with a leading space are not saved.</li>
        <li><strong>Command injection:</strong> Building commands from user input without sanitisation is dangerous. This is how many real attacks work.</li>
        <li><strong>Umask:</strong> Controls default permissions for new files. Check with <code>umask</code>. A value of <code>022</code> means new files are 644 (rw-r--r--).</li>
        <li><strong>Avoid running services as root:</strong> If an attacker exploits a service running as root, they own the system. Run services as dedicated low-privilege users.</li>
        <li><strong>Audit aliases:</strong> An alias like <code>alias sudo='sudo -i'</code> silently elevates all sudo calls to root shell. Check <code>alias</code> on unfamiliar machines.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- S12: Performance -->
    <div class="section" id="s12">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">🚀</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Performance Considerations</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 12 — Shell efficiency in scripts and pipelines</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="note note-perf">
        <div class="note-label">🚀 Performance Notes</div>
        <p>Shell is not meant for number-crunching. But pipelines can be dramatically faster when you avoid unnecessary processes.</p>
      </div>

      <pre><code><span class="comment"># SLOW: Useless Use of Cat (UUOC)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">cat</span> <span class="string">file.txt</span> | <span class="cmd-name">grep</span> <span class="string">"error"</span>     <span class="comment"># cat is unnecessary here</span>

<span class="comment"># FAST: grep reads the file directly</span>
<span class="cmd-name">grep</span> <span class="string">"error"</span> <span class="string">file.txt</span>

<span class="comment"># SLOW: For large files</span>
<span class="cmd-name">wc</span> <span class="flag">-l</span> < <span class="string">$(find /var/log -name "*.log")</span>  <span class="comment"># spawns many processes</span>

<span class="comment"># FAST: Use awk for multi-step text processing (fewer processes)</span>
<span class="cmd-name">awk</span> <span class="string">'/error/ {count++} END {print count}'</span> <span class="string">file.txt</span></code></pre>

      <ul>
        <li>Each process in a pipeline has startup overhead. Prefer single-program solutions (<code>awk</code>, <code>sed</code>) over chains of 5+ commands for large files.</li>
        <li>Built-in shell operations (<code>[[ ]]</code>, arithmetic <code>$(( ))</code>) are faster than forking external commands.</li>
        <li>For very large data processing, shell is the wrong tool — use Python, Go, or compiled programs instead.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- S13: Best Practices -->
    <div class="section" id="s13">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Best Practices — Senior Level</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 13 — How experienced engineers use the shell</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="senior-block">
        <h4>How a senior engineer thinks about the shell</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>They verify commands with <code>echo</code> or dry-run flags before destructive operations. Always.</li>
          <li>They document complex pipelines with comments in scripts — not just for others, but for future-self at 2am during an incident.</li>
          <li>They use <code>set -euo pipefail</code> at the top of every bash script — fail fast, fail loudly, fail early.</li>
          <li>They maintain a personal <code>~/.bashrc</code> snippet library backed up in git — the same aliases and functions across every server.</li>
          <li>They understand the startup file chain so they can diagnose "why isn't my variable set?" in 30 seconds.</li>
          <li>They use <code>tee</code> to both see and save output during critical operations.</li>
          <li>They don't pipe curl to bash. Ever.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <pre><code><span class="comment"># Professional script header (always start like this):</span>
#!/usr/bin/env bash
<span class="cmd-name">set</span> <span class="flag">-euo pipefail</span>    <span class="comment"># -e: exit on error, -u: error on unset var, -o pipefail: pipes fail correctly</span>
<span class="cmd-name">IFS</span>=<span class="string">$'\n\t'</span>           <span class="comment"># safer word splitting (no splitting on spaces)</span>

<span class="comment"># tee for visibility + logging:</span>
<span class="cmd-name">./deploy.sh</span> 2>&1 | <span class="cmd-name">tee</span> <span class="flag">-a</span> <span class="string">/var/log/deploys/$(date +%Y%m%d_%H%M%S).log</span></code></pre>
    </div>

    <!-- S14: Incidents -->
    <div class="section" id="s14">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="section-icon">🔥</div>
        <div>
          <div class="section-title">Real Incident Scenarios</div>
          <div class="section-num">Section 14 — What happens when shells go wrong in production</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="incident">
        <div class="incident-label">🚨 Production Incident — Simulation</div>
        <h4>The PATH Wipe Incident</h4>
        <p><strong>Scenario:</strong> A junior engineer edits <code>~/.bashrc</code> and writes <code>export PATH=/usr/local/myapp</code> instead of <code>export PATH="/usr/local/myapp:$PATH"</code>. They open a new SSH session.</p>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> <code>bash: ls: command not found</code>. ALL external commands fail. The engineer panics and closes the SSH session — locking themselves out of recovery too.</p>
        <p><strong>Recovery:</strong></p>
        <pre style="margin: 8px 0;"><code><span class="comment"># From a still-open session (never close all sessions!):</span>
<span class="cmd-name">export</span> <span class="string">PATH="/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin"</span>
<span class="cmd-name">nano</span> <span class="string">~/.bashrc</span>        <span class="comment"># fix the PATH line</span>
<span class="cmd-name">source</span> <span class="string">~/.bashrc</span>      <span class="comment"># verify it works before opening a new session</span></code></pre>
        <p><strong>Lesson:</strong> Always have a second SSH session open when modifying shell config files. Always append to PATH (<code>$PATH:</code>), never replace it. Always test with <code>bash -n ~/.bashrc</code> before sourcing.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="incident">
        <div class="incident-label">🚨 Production Incident — Simulation</div>
        <h4>The Accidental Overwrite</h4>
        <p><strong>Scenario:</strong> During a log rotation task, an engineer runs <code>gzip -c app.log > /var/log/app.log</code> instead of <code>gzip -c app.log > /var/log/app.log.gz</code>. The <code>></code> truncates app.log to zero bytes before gzip can read it.</p>
        <p><strong>Lesson:</strong> The <code>></code> redirection opens and truncates the destination <em>before</em> the command reads the source. If source and destination are the same file, data is lost. Always use different paths, or use a temp file + mv.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

