      <ul>
        <li><strong>Break 1 — Corrupt PATH in a subshell:</strong> Run <code>(export PATH="" && ls)</code>. Observe the error. Notice the outer shell is still fine. Now fix it in the subshell before exiting.</li>
        <li><strong>Break 2 — Variable with spaces:</strong> Try <code>MY VAR="hello"</code> (space in name). Read the error. Try <code>MY_VAR ="hello"</code> (space before =). Read the error. Then write it correctly.</li>
        <li><strong>Break 3 — Overwrite with <code>></code>:</strong> Create <code>test.txt</code> with content. Run <code>echo "" > test.txt</code>. Check what happened with <code>cat test.txt</code>. Understand why.</li>
        <li><strong>Break 4 — Syntax error in .bashrc (safe method):</strong> Add <code>echo "missing quote</code> (no closing quote) to a <em>test copy</em> of your bashrc. Run <code>bash -n /path/to/testrc</code> and see how bash reports the error.</li>
        <li><strong>Break 5 — Failed pipeline:</strong> Run <code>cat /nonexistent | grep something</code>. Check <code>echo $?</code>. Now run with <code>set -o pipefail</code> in a subshell and see how the exit code changes.</li>
